{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141217041249|638450253","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Steve_Stockman","to":"Steve Stockman"}],"pages":{"945590":{"pageid":945590,"ns":0,"title":"Steve Stockman","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-12-26T16:31:18Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{pp-blp|expiry=13 November 2014|small=yes}}\n{{For|the director|Steve Stockman (director)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name         = Steve Stockman\n|image        = Steve Stockman official portrait.jpg\n|state        = [[Texas]]\n|district     = {{ushr|Texas|36|36th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = <!--January 3, 2015-->\n|predecessor  = District created\n|successor    = [[Brian Babin]] <small>(elect)</small>\n|state1       = [[Texas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|Texas|9|9th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 1995\n|term_end1    = January 3, 1997\n|predecessor1 = [[Jack Brooks (politician)|Jack Brooks]]\n|successor1   = [[Nick Lampson]]\n|birthname    = Stephen Ernest Stockman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Patti Ferguson {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasmarriagerecords.org/marriage-of-stephen-stockman-and-patti-ferguson.html|title=Stephen Stockman and Patti Ferguson, Married December 10, 1988|publisher=texasmarriagerecords.org|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake|University of Houston, Clear Lake]]\n|religion     = [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Reiner |first=Anne |url=http://erlc.com/article/southern-baptist-contingent-in-congress-grows/ |title=Southern Baptist contingent in Congress grows |publisher=Erlc.com |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n|website      = [http://stockman.house.gov/ House website]\n}}\n'''Stephen Ernest \"Steve\" Stockman''' (born November 14, 1956) is an [[United States|American]] politician and member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] who is the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[Texas's 36th congressional district]]. Stockman previously served as the U.S. Representative for [[Texas's 9th congressional district]] from 1995 to 1997 and has served in his current position since 2013. Stockman ran in the [[United States Senate election in Texas, 2014|2014 election]] for the [[United States Senate]] but lost the Republican primary to incumbent Senator [[John Cornyn]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\n\nStockman was born in [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], outside [[Detroit]]. He graduated from [[Dondero High School]] in [[Royal Oak, Michigan|Royal Oak]], Michigan. From 1985 to 1986, he attended [[San Jacinto College]] but dropped out because he suffered from what he called \"partying syndrome\". In 1977, when Stockman was twenty, police officers found [[valium]] in his possession. He was charged with felony possession of a controlled substance, but the charge was later dropped.<ref name=Swartz>{{cite journal|author=Mimi Swartz |title=Congressman Clueless |journal=Texas Monthly |date=February 1996 |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/congressman-clueless/page/0/2}}</ref><ref name=Gillman>{{cite web|last=Gillman|first=Todd|title=In 1995, Stockman admitted jail time, felony charge. Today he denies that, accusing Cornyn allies of lying.|url=http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/in-1995-stockman-admitted-jail-time-felony-charge-today-he-denies-that-accusing-cornyn-allies-of-lying.html/|publisher=Dallas Morning News|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> He later turned around his life and became a [[Born again (Christianity)|born-again Christian]].<ref name=\"johngizzi\">John Gizzi, [http://www.humanevents.com/2012/07/07/steve-stockman-vies-for-36th-texas-district-seat/ Steve Stockman Vies for 36th Texas District Seat], ''[[Human Events]]'', July 7, 2012</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Christopher Hooks |title=Steve Stockman Can't Lose |date=December 20, 2013 |journal=Politico |url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-republican-primary-101412.html?hp=t1}}</ref> In 1990, he earned a bachelor's degree in [[accounting]] from the [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Salesman, 33, to run for Brooks seat|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=December 20, 1989|page=26}}</ref>  He worked as a computer salesman in [[Friendswood, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Local candidates rush to replace outgoing incumbents|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 11, 1990|author=Alan Bernstein|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1995\u20131997)==\n[[File:Steve stockman cong-bio-image.jpg|thumb|Stockman during his first stint in Congress]]\n\n===Elections===\n;1990\nStockman's first run for Congress in March 1990 in [[Texas's 9th congressional district]].  The district, anchored by [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]] and [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], had been represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Jack Brooks (politician)|Representative Jack Brooks]] since 1953.  His primary challenger was Mayor Maury Meyers of [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]].<ref name=brookswins>{{cite news|title=Primaries '90 - Rep. Brooks wins Dem contest; Meyers leads GOP opponent|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 15, 1990|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref> [[Oliver North]] made appearances at two of Stockman's fundraisers, for which he was paid $25,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran-contra figure North appears at Hance fund-raisers|publisher=''[[Dallas Morning News]]''|date=February 3, 1990|author=Sam Attlesey|quote=In addition to the fee he received for appearing with Mr. Hance, Mr. North also will receive $25,000 for joining Republican congressional candidate Steve Stockman on Saturday in Beaumont and Houston.}}</ref>\n\nMeyers got 44.3% of the primary vote; Stockman, 41%.<ref name=brookswins/>  Since no candidate had a majority, there was a runoff election and, with the support of third place finisher Steve Clifford,<ref name=loser>{{cite news|title=Loser backs Meyers in runoff|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 16, 1990|page=A25}}</ref> Meyers beat Stockman to win the Republican nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shine gets GOP nod in race for Congress|publisher=Austin American-Statesman|date=April 11, 1990|author1=Mike Ward|author2=Drew Parma|page=A9}}</ref>\n\n;1992\nStockman ran again in 1992 for the House in District 9. This time he was unopposed in the primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republican candidates|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 1, 1992|page=15|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  The [[1992 Republican National Convention]] was held in Houston in August of that year.  Candidate Stockman organized a \"congressional cruise\" on the [[Houston Ship Channel]] as a fundraising opportunity, but no members of Congress attended.<ref>{{cite news|title=National convention continues to have ripple effect locally|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=August 23, 1992|author=Alan Bernstein|page=C2}}</ref> Democrat Brooks defeated him 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news|title=House of Representatives [Part 2 of 2]|publisher=Sacramento Bee|date=November 5, 1992|page=A16}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nStockman ran again for House District 9 in 1994. He had two challengers in the Republican primary: John LeCour and James Milburn.  Stockman finished the primary with a [[Landslide victory|landslide]] 74%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election '94/Bentsen, Clark in runoff/District 25 victor to face Fontenot|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 9, 1994|author=Susan Warren}}</ref>\n\nHis Democratic opponent in the general election was, as before, incumbent Jack Brooks.  Initially the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) endorsed Brooks and even donated $5,000 to his cause, while the [[Gun Owners of America]] endorsed Stockman.<ref name=tenure>{{cite news|title=Rep. Brooks' long tenure in danger - The crime bill, his incumbency may sink the Democrat's bid for a 22nd term|publisher=Austin American-Statesman|date=October 22, 1994|page=A13}}</ref>  However, a number of NRA members threatened to resign from the organization over the issue and the NRA withdrew their support for Brooks, remaining neutral in the race.<ref name=tenure/>  In a major upset, Stockman beat Brooks, who, had he won, would have become [[Dean of the United States House of Representatives]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Texan in line as House dean - Jack Brooks has reputation as in-your-face politician|publisher=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=July 25, 1994|author=Ron Hutcheson|page=1}}</ref> by 51% to 49%.<ref>{{cite news|title=State Results|publisher=Austin American-Statesman|date=November 9, 1994|page=A8}}</ref>\n \n;1996\nStockman ran unopposed in the 1996 Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republicans|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=March 3, 1996|page=16|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  In July a federal court ordered the boundaries of 13 Texas House districts to be redrawn because of racial [[gerrymandering]], although Stockman's district was barely affected.<ref>{{cite news|title=The shape of things to come/Judges shift district lines/New races ordered this year for seats in Houston, Dallas|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=August 7, 1996|author=Alan Bernstein|quote=9th District:Few changes made; first-term conservative still running in a majority Democratic and Anglo district stretching from Galveston to Beaumont.}}</ref>  Stockman won a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] in the November election with 46%, forcing a runoff against Democratic [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]] assessor [[Nick Lampson]] in the runoff election.<ref>{{cite news|title=ELECTION '96/Stockman-Lampson runoff brawl may take place on national stage|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=November 7, 1996|page=34|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref>  Lampson won the runoff election with 53% of the vote<ref>{{cite news|title=Lampson, Brady, Bentsen win House seats in runoff election|publisher=Austin American-Statesman|date=December 11, 1996|author=Michael Graczyk|page=A10}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring his 1995 term, Stockman opposed the [[1994 economic crisis in Mexico|U.S. bailout of the Mexican peso]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|accessdate=February 13, 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=November 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman wrote an article for ''[[Guns & Ammo]]'' claiming that the [[Waco siege]] had been orchestrated by the Clinton administration in order \"to prove the need for a ban on so-called 'assault weapons.'\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Whatever Happened to the Class of 1994?: The right-wing firebrands who charged into Congress in 1994 launched the missile that impeached Bill Clinton. Now, more than a third of the renegades are out of office -- and those who remain are becoming Washington insiders. in out But it may have been a kamikaze mission|author=Dana Milbank|publisher=New York Times|date=January 17, 1999|section=Sunday Magazine|page=36}}</ref> He wrote further that \"[h]ad Bill Clinton really been unhappy with what Attorney General [[Janet Reno]] ordered, he would not only have fired her, he would have had Reno indicted for premeditated murder.\" After the article was published, Stockman's office denied that he believed in Waco \"conspiracy theories.\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Holmes|first=Steven A.|title=Terror in Oklahoma: In Congress; Congressman Calls Raid Near Waco A Clinton Plot|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/13/us/terror-in-oklahoma-in-congress-congressman-calls-raid-near-waco-a-clinton-plot.html|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 13, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Susan|title=Rep. Stockman Says Raid On Cult Had Political Aim|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 13, 1995|page=A08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman called for a Congressional investigation into [[Alfred Kinsey]]'s 1948 study ''[[Sexual Behavior in the Human Male]]'' after learning that Kinsey had used data from the diary of a pedophile.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Marc|title=Critics: Sex Ed A Sham Since Kinsey Used Pedophile's Data|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951212&slug=2157358|accessdate=1 February 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 December 1995}}</ref> Stockman believed that the allegations discredited current theories of [[sexual education]] in the United States, writing to his congressional colleagues that \u201c[o]ur children have been taught that . . . any type of sex is a valid outlet for their emotions. They are taught that the problem with sex is not that it is wrong to engage in homosexual, bestial, underage, or premarital sex, but that it is wrong to do so without protection.\u201d<ref name=Swartz/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|House Committee on Banking and Financial Services]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Griffith|first=Pat|title=Kaptur calls for date on Mexico bailout|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wF1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YQMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3735,2754040&dq=steve+stockman+committee&hl=en|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=Feb 11, 1995|location=Washington|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Digest|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9031D30874DC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=November 8, 1995}}</ref>\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n*[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|House Committee on Science]]<ref>http://congressmanstevestockman.com/meet-steve/</ref>\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Energy|Subcommittee on Energy]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n\n==Inter-congressional career (1997\u20142013)==\nIn 1998, Stockman ran unsuccessfully in the Republican primary for the [[Texas Railroad Commission]].<ref name=nr1/>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2007 Stockman worked with the conservative [[Leadership Institute]]<ref name=nr1/> as director of their [[Campus Leadership Program]].<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-36th-house-district-20121101 Texas, 36th House District] ''[[National Journal]]''. Retrieved December 17, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he attempted to run as an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] candidate for [[Texas's 22nd congressional district]], [[Tom DeLay]]'s former seat, but he failed to gather enough signatures to be placed on the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/politics/3994768.html |title=Stockman fails to get enough names - Houston Chronicle |publisher=Chron.com |date=2006-06-23 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref> However, Stockman did register for the special election to fill out the remainder of DeLay's term, one of five candidates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/candidates/2006con.pdf | title=Races with Candidates with Addresses Report | publisher=Texas Secretary of State | accessdate=2006-09-01|format=PDF}}</ref> He finished third, with 10.75% of the vote.\n\nDuring his time away from Congress, Stockman also cared for his father, who had [[Alzheimer's disease]]. The cost of caring for him meant that Stockman declared bankruptcy<ref>''In re Stephen E. Stockman and Patti F. Stockman'', case no. 02-33843-H3-7, U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of Texas (Houston Div.); petition filed April 5, 2002; discharge granted Oct. 24, 2002; case closed Oct. 24, 2002.</ref> and, when his father's disease became too severe, Stockman moved him to a veteran's home. When his father died, Stockman decided to run for Congress in the 2012 elections.<ref name=nr1/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2013\u2014Present)==\n\n===Election===\nIn 2011 Stockman formed an exploratory committee, Friends of Steve Stockman, to consider a run for the [[Texas's 14th congressional district|14th district]] seat being vacated by unsuccessful presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]]. Stockman instead ran in 2012 in the newly created 36th District, which includes his home in Friendswood. This district was drawn to be heavily Republican, and it was understood that whoever won the Republican primary would be the district's first congressman. In the May 29 primary, Stockman finished second in the first round, behind Stephen Vincent Takach (born c. 1962), a financial planner. Takach finished with 22 percent of the vote, far short of the 50 percent threshold required to win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may29_160_state.htm|title=Republican primary election returns, May 29, 2012|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref> Stockman won the July 31 runoff election, defeating Takach 55%-45% and thus assuring his return to Congress after a 16-year absence.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/primaries/congress/texas|title=Texas Congressional Primaries - Election Results|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|date=March 7, 2013|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November [[general election]], Stockman defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Max Owen Martin, a retired pilot from [[Clear Lake City, Texas]], with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov06_164_state.htm?x=0&y=8111&id=401|title=Texas general election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2013, Stockman was one of ten Republicans who didn't vote for [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) for [[Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], but the only representative to vote \"Present\" as his protest vote.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blake|first=Aaron|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/01/03/who-voted-against-boehner-for-speaker-and-why/ |title=Who voted against Boehner for speaker and why? |publisher=Washington Post |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=August 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kasperowicz |first=Pete |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/275419-boehner-re-elected-speaker-with-some-gop-defections#ixzz2HnwHNibn |title=Boehner reelected as Speaker; nine Republicans defect in vote - The Hill's Floor Action |publisher=Thehill.com |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>  He also opposes the [[Affordable Care Act]].<ref>http://www.thenewamerican.com/usnews/politics/item/17237-texas-cornyn-stockman-u-s-senate-race</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Stockman introduced \u201cThe Safe Schools Act,\u201d a bill that would repeal federal laws mandating \u201c[[Gun-free zone|gun free zones]]\u201d around schools in the wake of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] which took place in the previous month. He said \"I have one concern, protecting children from dangerous predators. By disarming qualified citizens and officials in schools we have created a dangerous situation for our children. In the 22 years before enactment of \u2018gun free school zones\u2019 there were two mass school shootings. In the 22 years since enactment of \u2018gun free schools\u2019 there have been 10 mass school shootings. Not only has the bill utterly failed to protect our children it appears to have placed them in danger.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourhoustonnews.com/bay_area/news/stockman-introduces-audit-the-fed-act-safe-schools-act-to/article_479e84a3-e51b-5360-80d8-34f47b23a242.html |title=Stockman introduces Audit The Fed Act, Safe Schools Act to repeal \u00e2\u20ac\u02dcGun Free School Zones\u00e2\u20ac\u2122 - Your Houston News: News |publisher=Your Houston News |date=2013-01-07 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref> The same month, Stockman issued a press release condemning [[gun control]] [[executive order]]s issued by [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] post-Sandy Hook, stating, \"I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing articles of [[impeachment]].\"<ref>{{cite press release |last=Stockman |first=Steve |title=Obama's gun grab an unconstitutional threat to the nation\n |date=January 14, 2013 |publisher=House.gov |location=Washington DC |url=http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-warns-obama-push-for-gun-control-will-be-met-with-white-house |accessdate=2013-01-18 |quote=The White House\u2019s recent announcement they will use executive orders and executive actions to infringe on our constitutionally-protected right to keep and bear arms is an unconstitutional and unconscionable attack on the very founding principles of this republic. I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing articles of impeachment.}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Stockman voted against the re-authorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]], objecting to provisions in the bill that expanded protections for transgendered victims of domestic violence. Stockman said, \"This is helping the liberals, this is horrible. Unbelievable. What really bothers \u2014 it's called a women's act, but then they have men dressed up as women, they count that. Change-gender, or whatever. How is that \u2014 how is that a woman?\"<ref name=nr1>{{cite news|last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |title=Back in the Saddle |date=March 18, 2013 |publisher=National Review |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/342824/back-saddle-betsy-woodruff |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political Positions==\n\n===Energy Independence===\nCongressman Stockman is a supporter of American energy independence and has used his position on the technology committee to question the EPA's technological criteria for evaluating applications on hydraulic fracking.<ref name=\"stockman.house.gov\">[http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/blog-posts/science-committee-questions-scientific-integrity-of-epa-hydraulic-fracturing].</ref> He has worked on improving the current technologies being used<ref name=\"stockman.house.gov\"/> on shale oil and gas production.  He is a member of the carbon caucus, supports the keystone pipeline, use of coal, opening up federal lands for drilling as well as hydraulic [[fracking]] for [[shale oil]] and gas production.\n\n===Economy and Jobs===\nStockman has spoken out about the need to dredge and secure the Texas Ports like Houston, Cedar Bayou, Beaumont and Orange from which many of the Gulf Coast petrochemicals are shipped, providing a considerable number of jobs, as these ports are important to the Texan economy.<ref>[http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/3dcf1362#/3dcf1362/28]</ref> The district includes Baytown, Pasadena, Deer Park, Mount Bellvieu and is the largest petrochemical industrial district in the United States.<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/TX/36]</ref> With the advent of production of shale gas, over 100 billion dollars are expected to be invested in the U.S. petrochemical sector over the next few years (most of it in Texas), and over 40 billion dollars in Stockman\u2019s district, potentially creating numerous new jobs.<ref>[http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/3dcf1362#/3dcf1362/28]</ref> These plants include ethylene crackers, PDH plants, methanol manufacturing facilities and others. Stockman has repeatedly appealed to the EPA to expedite permits for new plant construction.<ref>[http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-gets-promise-from-epa-to-unclog-texas-jobs-pipeline-offers-to Press release]</ref> He has also called on vice president [[Biden]] to obtain a lifting of what he argues is an EPA blockade on American jobs.<ref>[http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-challenges-biden-to-lift-epa-blockade-on-port-jobs Press release]</ref> In a statement, Stockman has said that unless the EPA is reformed by streamlining permits and studies and approving the REINS Act, the United States will cease to be an economic power. The \"Regulations from the Executive In Need of Scrutiny,\" or REINS, Act would require that any proposed federal regulation costing more than $100 million be approved by Congress and signed by the President.\n\nAt 3.5 cents per kilowatt hour, Texas industrial facilities enjoy one of the cheapest power costs in the world, which Stockman argues is conducive to investment and job growth and encourages employment. Stockman has favored keeping power costs low.<ref>[http://science.house.gov/sites/republicans.science.house.gov/files/documents/Letters/121913_mccarthy.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/blog-posts/scalise-anti-carbon-tax-amendment-passed-by-house Press release]</ref>\n\n===Views on the Constitution===\nCongressman Stockman belongs to the Libertarian wing of the Republican Party which believes in small government and keeping government out of peoples lives. He has been known for his strong stand on the protection of Second Amendment Rights. He has always stood up against the Executive branch and included impeachment as a resort when he felt the constitution has been violated. He has worked with Rand Paul and introduced \u201cRestore The Constitution Act.\u201d That provision is the House companion to Sen. Rand Paul's \u201cSeparation of Powers Restoration and Second Amendment Protection Act.\u201d Stockman and Paul are working together on the effort.<ref>[http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-introduces-bill-to-stop-obama-s-executive-orders Press release]</ref>\n\n===Fiscal===\nCongressman Stockman has never voted for a tax increase and has been a proponent for spending cuts and small government.<ref>http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-will-vote-against-reckless-debt-spending-proposal</ref>  He cosponsored 2013 Energy Freedom Prosperity Act that would eliminate all energy-related tax subsidies.<ref>[http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/3dcf1362#/3dcf1362/28]</ref>  He sponsored the bill to defund \"Obamacare\".  Stockman wants to eliminate the [[Internal Revenue Service]] and establish a [[flat tax]].{{Cn|date=October 2014}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thevindicator.com/news/article_3dee5bbc-5b45-11e2-986f-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Stockman named to Science, Foreign Affairs committees - The Vindicator: News |publisher=The Vindicator |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref>\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research|Subcommittee on Research]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n==2014 U.S. Senate election==\nOn December 9, 2013, Stockman filed for the Republican nomination for U.S. Senate for Texas against incumbent U.S. Senator [[John Cornyn]].<ref name=\"WoodruffNR12092013\">Woodruff, Betsy. [http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/365887/stockman-will-primary-cornyn-betsy-woodruff Stockman Will Primary Cornyn], ''[[National Review]]'', December 9, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"GlueckPolitico12092013\">{{cite web | last = Glueck | first = Katie | title = In surprise, Steve Stockman challenges John Cornyn | work = [[Politico]] | date = December 9, 2013 | url = http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-primary-100924.html?hp=f3}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2014, Stockman polled 250,759 votes (19.2 percent) in his bid for the Republican nomination for the Senate.<ref>\"Cornyn easily wins GOP nomination for US Senate,\" Associated Press, March 4, 2014, from KHOU-TV Houston, at [http://www.khou.com/news/election/US-Sen-Cornyn-wins-Republican-nomination-in-Texas-248474551.html].</ref> He placed second in a field of eight candidates on the ballot. Cornyn received 778,967 votes (59.44 percent).<ref name=\"enr.sos.state.tx.us\">{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176|title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Texas 2014 Primary Results|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2014/results/primaries/texas|accessdate=6 March 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>  On election night, Stockman quickly conceded and called upon Texas Republicans to vote the straight party ticket on November 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2014/03/04/cornyn-crushes-stockman-in-texas-primary/|title=Mary Katherine Ham, \"Cornyn crushes Stockman in Texas primary\", March 4, 2014|publisher=hotair.com|accessdate=March 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile [[Brian Babin]] is the Republican nominee for District 36 as Stockman did not contest this seat.\n\n==Ethics investigation regarding former campaign worker==\n\nOn April 25, 2014, Stockman stated that the Ethics Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives is investigating a campaign finance reporting error made by a former campaign worker. Stockman stated that the mistake was corrected soon after he learned of it, and that the worker had been removed from the campaign organization.<ref>Matthew Daly, \"Texas Rep. Stockman says ethics inquiry underway,\" April 26, 2014, Associated Press, at [http://news.yahoo.com/texas-rep-stockman-says-ethics-inquiry-underway-215614889.html].</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Michigan|Texas|Politics|Conservatism|Christianity}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://stockman.house.gov/ Representative Steve Stockman] official U.S. House site\n*[http://congressmanstevestockman.com/ Steve Stockman for Congress]\n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Steve_Stockman_%5BR-36%5D|Steve Stockman}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = S000937 | ballot = Steve_Stockman | nndb = 399/000168892 | votesmart = 21703